<br>
But that's just <i><b><u>my</u></b></i> opinion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/utheyanger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>The Yanger </A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www1.iswest.com/theyanger/y.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1784<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(3/1/02 11:09:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=250.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: NeverWinter Nights and the Monk</span><hr size=1> Being a Gravedigger or Child Killer greatly affects the initial reactions of NPCs. Trust me on that one.<br>
I'm sorry but fallout 2 is pretty damn non-linear. The first game is more linear with less options, but it's still way better than BG. If you think the story of Fallout 2 amounts to 'oh no get the geck' you are on crack. The coolest part is that you can discover the story and your objectives any damn way you choose. Sure there IS a direct route that you can follow, but there's nothing stopping you from going to say, New Reno, before you go to Klamath and finding out some information. <br>
Combat: I'm sorry, but the combat in fallout is excellent. Sure you only control one character, but so frickin what? The system is excellently balanced for one character (or if you play fallout tactics you can control 6). If you think Burst or aimed is as far as combat goes you're mistaken. APs work for everything and it really makes you consider every action. Do I want to dig into my pockets this turn and use some stimpacks? (2 ap for inventory use). Do I want to get closer to increase my aim and go for one shot, or do I wanna stay out here and have enough AP to shoot twice? Do I wanna use burst fire and risk pureeing that civilian, or just do a single shot and hope I kill this enemy? Do I aim at his groin for maximum damage, or do I aim at his eyes to decrease his hit percentage?<br>
It goes on and on and on.<br>
As far as depth of character goes, I was referring to the skills you can choose, not the titles (which are more of a roleplaying thing anyway). The stats you choose greatly affect your character, the traits you choose greatly affect your character, the skills you tag and raise greatly affect your character, and the perks you gain as you level greatly affect your character. It's difficult to raise a character exactly the same as someone else without really trying. It leads to characters that are incredibly specialized and more entertaining to get through the game with.<br>
We're talking about the difference between Half Life and Deus Ex here. Half Life is a decent game, but in the end it's just a good shooter. deus ex is a shooter where the choices you make about your character will affect not just simple NPC reactions, but HOW YOU DO everything in the game.<br>
I also admire the fallout series for the ability to be pretty much however good or evil you want to be straight from the start. There's nothing preventing you from insulting everyone you meet, slaughtering them to take their items, joining morally bankrupt organizations...and at the same time you can join police forces and the like and put a stop to these activities. The only thing that needed more work really was the last level, since as far as I know you can't actually join the bad guys (you can parade around as one until the last boss though, thus avoiding all combat in the base. Very handy).<br>
Even the NPCs you choose to take with you can make a large difference with many situations in the game. And perhaps the most rewarding aspect of all the possibilities, is that it has many different scripts describing what happens to every town or faction after you beat the game, giving you a feeling of closure =p Arcanum does this too, but I've found there are less possibilites for most towns in that game. IE: I saved the bessie toone mine in Shrouded Hills, thus triggering the 'boomtown' ending, but it kinda ignored the fact that after saving the mine I slaughtered the town.<br>
